The routing configuration can be defined in the startup class of your application. 

In an ASP.NET Core application, the routing configuration typically resides in the `Configure` method of the `Startup` class. Within this method, you can use the `app.UseEndpoints` or `app.UseMvc` method to define the routing configuration.

Example:
```csharp
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
{
    // Other configuration code

    app.UseRouting();

    app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>
    {
        endpoints.MapControllerRoute(
            name: "default",
            pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");
    });
}
```

In this example, the `UseEndpoints` method is used to define the routing configuration. The `MapControllerRoute` method is used to map the controller and action names to specific routes. The `pattern` parameter defines the route pattern, where the segments within curly braces represent the controller, action, and optional parameters.

It's important to note that the routing configuration can vary depending on the version of ASP.NET Core you are using and the specific requirements of your application.
